<h2>
    <strong>Understanding the Summer Steelhead</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    Summer steelhead (Oncorhynchus mykiss) are sea-run rainbow trout that return to freshwater between April and October. Unlike their winter counterparts, summer steelhead enter rivers earlier and typically remain longer, offering a prolonged fishing season. They are leaner, faster, and more aggressive during the warmer months—qualities that make them a favorite among sport fishers.
</p>
<p>
    Unlike salmon, steelhead do not die after spawning. Many survive and return to the ocean, which makes proper handling and catch-and-release practices crucial. Summer fish often travel farther upriver and hold in different locations than winter fish. Knowing these behavioral patterns can help anglers better understand how, when, and where to target them effectively.
</p>
<p>
