<h2>
    <strong>Common Mistakes to Avoid When Targeting Summer Steelhead</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    Even seasoned anglers can make missteps. Here are the most common mistakes to watch out for:
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Fishing during the heat of the day</strong> – Summer steelhead tend to go deep or become inactive when the sun is high. Stick to mornings or evenings.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Using heavy gear</strong> – These fish are wary. Oversized tackle can spook them and reduce your hook-up rate.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Ignoring regulations</strong> – Make sure you’re fishing legally with the correct license, tags, and gear restrictions.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Not checking river flows</strong> – High or murky water can render some areas unfishable.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Poor catch-and-release technique</strong> – Mishandling fish or taking too long to release can cause unnecessary mortality. Use barbless hooks and wet hands before handling.
    </li>
</ol>
<p>
    Avoid these pitfalls and you’ll have a better chance at a successful, respectful outing.
